India, however, is believed to have close to 100 fully reliable warheads. <br>
Obviously, any use of a nuclear weapon would be an unprecedented human tragedy. It is just as obvious that there is little that we, as a group, can do to prevent it. I think, however, that we should prepare for the possibility by discussing the likely effects and our response to them.<br>
It would almost certainly be Pakistan that introduced nukes into the war, since their conventional forces are at a huge disadvantage. India would have to hold back a sizable percentage of its nukes as a deterrent against China. These factors mitigate against a really large scale exchange, since Pakistan has few weapons and India will not use any more than they have to. Millions could be killed, but this depends largely on the target selection. If only military forces are targeted, civilian deaths would still be horrific, but not as bad as if cities were hit on purpose.<br>
Public reaction in the rest of the world would be extreme, completely dwarfing September 11. We can expect the most extreme possible response from the anti-nuclear industry, regardless of the conflict's actual intensity. Quite simply, they and their followers will predict, and expect, the end of all life through fall-out. Many of those who have been brainwashed by the anti-nuke movement may in fact be surprised that the fireballs themselves don't reach to the US or Australia or cause worldwide earthquakes. Whatever happens, it is very unlikely to be as bad as the anti-nuclear movement and the general public expect. It will be bad enough, to be sure, but nothing like total extinction or nuclear winter or a quantum jump in global cancer rates, which is what 50 years of anti-nuclear demonlogy have led people to expect.<br>
