However tragic it may be a thermonuclear war is inevitable eventually. Maybe if we had chosen to put more research into understanding and better controlling the nuclear genie we might have less fear of it. It is difficult to defend against a comparatively unknown threat. There is so much more study we could have done in the last 50 years. Instead we stuck our heads in the sand and prayed that the poorer nations were too dumb to discover this 40's technology.<br>
India and Pakistan have tested the bomb but I am certain many other nations know how to build one and may have done so on the sly. Perhaps even nations friendly top Iraq. Who knows.<br>
I don't think it will make a great deal of difference to the world in the long run if nukes are used. In the short run it will be big news and millions may die. Hiroshima and Nagasaki all over again. Primitive nukes destroying all the major cities of Pakistan and perhaps some of India. Pakistan has access to very little weapons grade material.<br>
In the long run it will be just like the bombing of Japan. A footnote in history. I can't see how it could escalate any further. That may sound heartless but I am trying to think rationally and not deliver a torrent of emotional mouthings. One of my best friends is Indian and both countries have seen enough war already.<br>
I wish I could say that it is just more hype but I can see these two eternal foes really doing it. Atomic war is inevitable because there will always be both hate in the world and hydrogen bombs. You can't uninvent something and as long as it is known to be possible someone will strive to build it. Only by completely taking away all of our freedoms could we prevent any atomic weapon from being secretly built and used. That in my opinion would be worse than death. <br>
